This directory contains the Ivy documentation web site, built with Jekyll
(https://jekyllrb.com/). The Gemfile here pins the Jekyll version, so the
site builds the same way locally and in CI.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Prerequisites: Ruby and Bundler
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

You need a reasonably modern Ruby (>= 3.0). Check what you have:

    $ ruby --version

The Ruby that ships with macOS (2.6) is too old, so install a current one
with Homebrew (https://brew.sh):

    $ brew install ruby

Homebrew's Ruby is "keg-only" (it does not replace the system Ruby), so add
it to your PATH -- put this in your ~/.zshrc (or ~/.bash_profile) and open a
new shell:

    export PATH="$(brew --prefix ruby)/bin:$PATH"

Confirm the new Ruby is in use (should print the Homebrew version, not 2.6):

    $ which ruby && ruby --version

Bundler ships with Ruby; if it is missing, install it with:

    $ gem install bundler

(On Linux, install Ruby with your package manager, e.g.
`sudo apt-get install ruby-full build-essential`, then use Bundler as below.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Building and viewing the site locally
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Install the gems listed in the Gemfile (run once, and again whenever the
Gemfile changes):

    $ cd doc
    $ bundle install

Then serve the site with live reload:

    $ bundle exec jekyll serve --livereload

and open http://localhost:4000/ . The server rebuilds as you edit; use
--port N to choose a different port, or drop --livereload if you prefer.

To just generate the static site into _site/ without serving:

    $ bundle exec jekyll build

The _site/ output, the Bundler vendor/ directory, and Gemfile.lock are all
git-ignored.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Deploying the site to GitHub Pages
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Deployment is automatic. The workflow .github/workflows/pages.yml builds
this directory with the same Gemfile and publishes it to GitHub Pages on
every push to the master branch (it can also be run manually from the
Actions tab). There is no longer a gh-pages branch or a manual "deploy"
script: in the repository settings, Pages must be configured with
"Source: GitHub Actions".
